RATE SCHEDULE FOR THE SALE, ASSIGNMENT, OR TRANSFER OF TRANSMISSION RIGHTS ON NON-JURISDICTIONAL TRANSMITTING UTILITY SYSTEMS
RATE SCHEDULE FOR THE SALE, ASSIGNMENT, OR TRANSFER OF TRANSMISSION RIGHTS ON NON-JURISDICTIONAL TRANSMITTING UTILITY SYSTEMS
1. General Purpose: The purpose of this rate schedule is to provide for the sale, assignment, or transfer of transmission rights by Seller on non- jurisdictional transmitting utility systems in which the transmission provider does not play the intermediary role in secondary market transmission transactions as contemplated under the reforms that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("Commission") adopted in Order No. 890.
2. Duration: This rate schedule shall continue in effect until terminated or changed and such termination or change becomes effective in accordance with any applicable regulatory requirements.
3. Services To Be Rendered: Seller may sell, assign, or transfer to a purchaser, pursuant to an agreement negotiated between them, all or a portion of Selleres rights to the use of the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility system that Seller has reserved for its own use under a service agreement with the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility or under a service agreement it has acquired from another customer. The purchaser must be an eligible customer under the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility's open access transmission tariff or other tariffs pursuant to which the transmission rights to be transferred to the purchaser were originally obtained from the transmission provider.
4. Sale of Transmission Rights: Seller may sell transmission rights that Seller has reserved for its own use from the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility. Seller may sell, assign, or transfer such transmission rights at the price provided below.
5. Terms and Conditions:
a. Except for price and creditworthiness, the terms and conditions under which Seller will sell, assign, or transfer transmission rights on the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility system to a purchaser shall be the terms and conditions governing the original grant of such transmission rights by the transmission provider.
b. Should the customers creditworthiness, financial responsibility, or performance viability become unsatisfactory to Seller in Sellers sole, reasonably exercised discretion, Seller may require the Customer to provide, at the Customers option, either (i) the posting of a letter of credit, (ii) a cash prepayment, (iii) a guarantee, or (iv) the posting of other acceptable collateral or security by the Customer. If the Customer fails to provide such satisfactory assurances of its ability to perform
a transaction hereunder within three (3) business days of demand therefore, Seller (in addition to exercising any and all remedies available at law or in equity, expressly inclusive of, but not limited to withholding, setting off against or recouping from amounts otherwise due) (i) may suspend performance of the transaction, or (ii) immediately terminate the transaction, and calculating the amount of its costs, expenses, and losses incurred due to the Customers inability to perform, and presenting the Customer with a demand therefore which must be paid within three (3) business days of receipt. In determining whether the Customer has provided satisfactory assurances and in determining the action to be taken, Seller may suspend performance or terminate the transaction without making a filing at FERC.
6. Compensation: Seller shall sell, assign, or transfer any transmission rights pursuant to this rate schedule at a price mutually agreed to between Seller and purchaser.
7. Modifications: Seller may unilaterally apply to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this rate schedule under section 205 of the Federal Power Act and the regulations promulgated thereunder.
